{"user_message": {"title": "Code Review — APPROVE (with notes) — Ledger amount validation (ADR 0001)", "content": "## Code Review — Monetary amount input validation (ADR 0001)\n\n**Scope reviewed:** `src/features/ledger/lib/amount.ts`, `lib/ingest.ts`, `lib/amount.test.ts`, `index.ts` (barrel). Contract verified against `features/ledger/types.ts` and `wealth-score/lib/compute.ts`.\n\n**Review status:** COMPLETE — all target files read in full; `tsc --noEmit` clean for the new modules; sign convention confirmed empirically.\n\n### Strengths\n- Clean pure-function boundary matching repo convention (`customers/lib/normalize.ts`). No I/O, no side effects.\n- Sign convention is correct and load-bearing: `compute.ts:19-20,84-85` keys income/expense on `amount > 0` / `< 0`; `parseAmount` signs by `direction`, and rejecting `zero` (`amount.ts:88,95`) protects the `<= 0`/`> 0` branches from a $0 row landing on the wrong side.\n- Float handling is sound: `roundToCents` + epsilon `hasAtMostCents` (`amount.ts:114-121`) correctly accepts `70.7`/`1284.5` while rejecting `10.001`.\n- `isValidSignedAmount` mirrors the invariants for stored values — good defense in depth.\n\n### Findings\n\n**Critical:** none.\n**High:** none.\n\n**Medium**\n- `amount.ts:73,77` — *Number coercion accepts non-decimal numeric forms.* After stripping `[$,\\s]`, `Number(cleaned)` accepts scientific notation, hex, and binary literals: `\"1e5\"`→`100000`, `\"0x10\"`→`16`, `\"1e3\"`→`1000`. An adversarial/garbled SMS or OCR body could silently coerce to a plausible amount (huge values are caught by `out-of-range`, but mid-range ones like `\"1e5\"` pass as valid). **Fix:** validate the cleaned string against a money shape before coercion — `if (!/^\\d+(\\.\\d{1,2})?$/.test(cleaned)) return { ok:false, error:\"not-a-number\" };`. This also subsumes the `too-many-decimals` and `not-a-number` string paths, tightening the boundary.\n\n**Low**\n- `ingest.ts:60-68` — *Only `amount` is validated; `date`, `category`, `description`, `confidence`, `customerId` pass through untouched.* An invalid `date` string or out-of-[0,1] `confidence` produces a malformed `Transaction`. This is adjacent to the requested scope (the boundary was scoped to amounts) — noting separately, not gating. **Fix (follow-up):** add lightweight shape checks (ISO-date, `0 ≤ confidence ≤ 1`) at the same seam, or file as a scoped task.\n- `amount.ts:78` + `:85` — *Redundant `Number.isNaN(n)` check.* The string path returns at `:78`; the `:85` guard covers the numeric-input NaN case. Harmless but the `:78` early-return can be dropped if the regex fix above is adopted (it would catch non-numeric strings first). **Fix:** consolidate once the regex guard lands.\n- `amount.test.ts:5` — *Tests cannot run in CI.* `tsx` is not a dependency and no test script exists (`package.json` has only Playwright e2e). The 12 cases are sound but unexecutable in the pipeline. Tracked as ADR task 4 — confirm it lands before relying on these as a regression gate.\n\n### Verdict\n**APPROVE (with notes).** No security or critical/correctness issues; the implementation is correct, well-typed, and consistent with the codebase. The medium finding (numeric-literal coercion) is a real input-hardening gap worth fixing before the live SMS/OCR adapter (ADR task 5) routes untrusted strings through this boundary, but it does not gate this changeset — large mis-parses are bounded by `out-of-range`. Recommend addressing the regex hardening in the same PR or as the first commit of task 5.", "content_type": "success", "priority": "normal"}}

